<p><b>Edgar Morin</b> is a <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">French</a> <a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher" class="mw-redirect">philosopher</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sociologist" title="Sociologist" class="mw-redirect">sociologist</a> who was born in <a href="/wiki/Paris" title="Paris">Paris</a> on <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1921-07-08"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="07-08"><a href="/wiki/July_8" title="July 8">July 8</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1921" title="1921">1921</a></span> under the original name <b>Edgar Nahoum</b>. He is of Judeo-Spanish (<a href="/wiki/Sefardi" title="Sefardi" class="mw-redirect">Sefardi</a>) origin. He is known for the <a href="/wiki/Transdisciplinarity" title="Transdisciplinarity">transdisciplinarity</a> of his works, in that he covers a wide range of interests and dismisses the conventional boundaries between <a href="/wiki/Academic_discipline" title="Academic discipline" class="mw-redirect">academic disciplines</a>.</p>
